The paper deals with the study of behavioral metrics in an abstract setting, which is a topic that is relevant to several subfields of computer science. The paper also mentions the Kantorovich and Wasserstein pseudometrics, which are commonly used in the analysis of probability measures, indicating a possible connection to cs.CC and cs.DM.
